<section xml:id="sec_the_derivatives_tutor">
  <title>The Derivatives Tutor</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
          <idx><h>derivative</h><h>tutor</h></idx>
    </p>
    <p>
      The Derivatives tutor is a useful way for visualising the graphs of the first
      (and second)
      derivatives of a given function.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Opening up the Derivatives tutor using menus.</caption>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=\textwidth]{tutorials/figures/DerivativeTutorLoad1-eps-converted-to.pdf}
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <caption>Opening up the Derivatives tutor using commands. The <c>Student[Calculus1]</c> package is required.</caption>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=\textwidth]{tutorials/figures/DerivativeTutorLoad2-eps-converted-to.pdf}
    </figure>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Visualising the Derivative of <m>(x-1)^2\sin(x)</m></title>
    <figure>
      <caption>The Derivatives tutor displays the given function <m>f(x)</m> as well as its derivative(s) <m>f'(x)</m> (and optionally <m>f''(x)</m>).</caption>
      <image width="80%" source="images/DerivativeTutorQ1-1-eps-converted-to.png"/>
      \vspace{-1cm}
    </figure>
    <aside>
      <p>
        When typing out the function in the tutor,
        you will not have access to the palettes toolbar in Maple.
        You will need to type out commands such as <c>sqrt()</c> for square roots.
        You must also include the symbol * for multiplication.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <figure>
      <caption>You can optionally specify the axes ranges as well as <m>1:1</m> scaling.</caption>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=\textwidth,trim={{0.2\width} 0 0 0},clip]{tutorials/figures/DerivativeTutorQ1-2-eps-converted-to.pdf}
    </figure>
  </subsection>
</section>